column168: WHILE UNLOADING PALLET #7236 OFF EMERY HUT TRUCK, ONE OF MY AGENTS NOTICED A LIQUID LEAKING FROM AN ICE CHEST THAT WAS BUILT ON THE PALLET.  THE ICE CHEST HAD FALLEN ON ITS SIDE DURING THE TRIP FROM THE EMERY FACILITY TO THE AIRCRAFT.  THE AGENT TURNED THE ICE CHEST UPRIGHT TO STOP THE LEAK AND THEN CAME IN AND NOTIFIED ME OF THE SITUATION.  UPON FURTHER EXAMINATION I DIS- COVERED THAT THE LEAKING ICE CHEST CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (POISONOUS LIQUIDS N.O.S.).  I ADVISED THE AGENT TO STOP THE OPERATION UNTIL I INVES- TIGATED THE SITUATION FURTHER. I THEN PLACED A CALL TO CHEMTREC TO RECEIVE FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS.  DURING THE INSPECTION OF THE ICE CHEST I DISCOVERED A BROKEN JAR.  BELIEVING THE SPILT LIQUID TO BE CONTAMINATED, I HAD THE AREA CLEARED AND NOTIFIED PORT AUTHORITY FIRE & POLICE DEPT.  I ALSO NOTIFI ED THE PROPER SUMMIT & EMERY PERSONNEL OF THE SITUATION. SEVEN SUMMIT EMP- LOYEES (INCLUDING MYSELF) WERE TAKEN TO ST. JAMES HOSPITAL FOR DECONTAMI- NATION.  I BELIEVE THE TRIP FROM EMERY WAREHOUSE TO THE AIRCRAFT CAUSED THE CHEST TO FALL ON ITS SIDE.  IF MORE CARE WAS TAKEN IN THE BUILD UP & SE- CURING OF THE PALLET THIS INCIDENT POSSIBLY COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED.  IT IS ALSO POSSIBLE THAT THE CONTENTS COULD HAVE BEEN PACKAGED BETTER.
